security.

The container has to clear screening.

They won't open it.

MALIK
It was transferred by the funeral home
this morning.

CHECK-IN AGENT
Then you've done what you can.

Malik does not like the sentence.

What you can.

She tags the checked bags through to Lagos.

The printer chatters.

Four boarding passes.

She hands them to Malik.

CHECK-IN AGENT (CONT'D)
I'm sorry for your loss.

This time Malik does not say thank you automatically.

He looks at the carry case.

MALIK
So are we.

INT. VANCOUVER INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT - SECURITY - LATER

Belts.

Shoes.

Laptops.

The small undressing required by flight.

Kai places his camera in a bin.

Ade places his watch beside it.

Bode removes nothing until asked.

Malik places the padded carry case in its own bin.

He keeps one hand on it.

SCREENING OFFICER
Sir.

Malik lets go.

The case enters the X-ray.

The conveyor carries Solomon away.

Malik walks through the metal detector.

Clear.

Ade.

Clear.

Kai.

The alarm sounds.

Kai freezes.

Feels inside his jacket.

The sealed passport envelope.

The brass key remains taped inside it.

Still unopened.

KAI
I forgot.

MALIK
You packed it.

KAI
That is not the same thing.

Kai places the entire sealed envelope in a tray.

Bode passes through.

Clear.

The envelope follows Solomon into the machine.

The officer studies a monitor.

Stops the conveyor.

Malik sees the padded case still inside the machine.

Motionless.

MALIK
What's wrong?

SCREENING OFFICER
One moment, please.

MALIK
The container is sealed.

SCREENING OFFICER
I understand.

MALIK
You cannot open it.

SCREENING OFFICER
We won't.

She calls a SUPERVISOR.

Quietly.

Professionally.

Malik hears only the call.

The supervisor examines the image.

The brothers wait on the wrong side of their father.

Passengers collect their belongings around them.

Reassemble their lives.

Move on.

Malik cannot.

His hands open.

Close.

Open again.

Ade sees.

ADE
Dad making us late.

Malik looks at him.

ADE (CONT'D)
Growth.

The joke does not dismiss the fear.

It gives it somewhere to stand.

The supervisor nods.

The conveyor starts.

Solomon emerges.

The officer does not touch the sealed urn.

She swabs the outside of the padded case.

Waits for the machine.

Green.

SCREENING OFFICER
You're clear.

Malik takes the case.

Holds it against his chest.

Not like luggage.

Bode retrieves the sealed envelope.

Offers it to Kai.

Kai does not take it.

KAI
You keep it.

Bode studies him.

Slips the unopened envelope inside his coat.

The first piece of Solomon's plan Kai has chosen not to carry.

INT. VANCOUVER INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT - DEPARTURE GATE - MORNING

Dawn makes the runway blue.

The brothers sit in a row.

Malik.

Ade.

Kai.

Bode stands at the window.

The padded carry case rests beneath Malik's knees.

His hand remains on the handle.

Ade unwraps four breakfast sandwiches.

Offers one to Malik.

Malik shakes his head.

Offers one to Kai.

Kai is filming the departure board.

ADE
You can document chewing.

KAI
I have.

ADE
And this is why nobody visits.

Ade gives the fourth sandwich to Bode.

Bode accepts it.

Behind him, aircraft cross the wet tarmac.

ADE (CONT'D)
When did you last go back?

BODE
Eight months ago.

ADE
You go often?

BODE
Often enough to remain disappointing
in two countries.

Ade smiles.

A line worth keeping.

MALIK
Who were you talking to last night?

Bode looks at him.

Kai stops filming.

BODE
Cousin Eyo.

He keeps the house.

MALIK
You said they don't know.

BODE
They do not know what Solomon told you.

MALIK
Which is nothing.

BODE
Then everyone is equally prepared.

BOARDING AGENT (O.S.)
We are now inviting passengers requiring
additional time to board.

Bode looks at the carry case.

Then at Malik.

BODE
That is us.

Malik starts to object.

Bode is already walking.

For once, Malik follows.

INT. INTERNATIONAL AIRCRAFT - NIGHT

The cabin has forgotten morning.

Window shades closed.

Faces lit by private screens.

The four men occupy one row divided by an aisle.

Kai at the window.

Ade in the middle.

Malik on the aisle.

Bode directly across.

The padded carry case fits beneath Malik's seat.

His shoes bracket it.

Protective.

Possessive.

Ade attempts sleep with a neck pillow that has rotated beneath his chin.

Kai watches the flight map.

A white line arcs toward West Africa.

The plane icon crosses a dark Atlantic.

Malik completes a Nigerian arrival form.

Block letters.

No mistakes.

PURPOSE OF VISIT:

He writes:

FAMILY.

Stares at it.

Adds:

FUNERAL.

Across the aisle, Bode sleeps.

Or performs sleep convincingly.

Kai zooms the flight map.

LAGOS glows at the end of the route.

The screen refreshes.

LAGOS disappears.

The route continues toward an unnamed coastline.

Kai sits forward.

The plane icon moves.

Destination:

Blank.

He touches the screen.

Nothing.

The map refreshes again.

LAGOS returns.

Ade opens one eye.

ADE
Did we miss Africa?

KAI
The name disappeared.

ADE
Maybe it needed privacy.

Kai looks at Malik.

Malik saw.

KAI
You saw it.

MALIK
The screen refreshed.

KAI
It removed only the destination.

MALIK
Then complain to the airline.

KAI
That's not what I'm saying.

MALIK
I know.

Malik looks down at the carry case beneath his feet.

MALIK (CONT'D)
And we are still on the plane.

Not denial.

A boundary.

Kai leans back.

Outside the window—

Nothing but his reflection.

Behind it, somewhere below—

An ocean without names.

HOURS LATER

The cabin lights brighten by degrees.

Artificial dawn.

Ade sleeps against Kai's shoulder.

Kai allows it.

Malik is awake.

Still holding the completed form.

Bode is awake too.

They regard each other across the aisle.

MALIK
What did he leave?

Bode knows who he means.

BODE
Canada?

MALIK
Calabar.

BODE
First?

Malik waits.

BODE (CONT'D)
His mother.

His brother.

His language, when he was angry.

The river.

Then other things.

MALIK
Her?

Bode looks toward Kai.

Eyes closed.

Perhaps sleeping.

BODE
Ask me when we arrive.

MALIK
Will the answer change?

BODE
You may.

Malik almost pushes.

Doesn't.

The FASTEN SEAT BELT sign illuminates.

The aircraft begins to descend.

Bode opens his window shade.

Morning enters all at once.

Below—

Lagos extends beyond the window.

Roads.

Roofs.

Water.

No single frame can contain it.

Kai opens his eyes.

For once—

Does not reach for the camera.

INT. MURTALA MUHAMMED AIRPORT - ARRIVALS - DAY

The terminal is bright with movement.

Families.

Business travellers.

Porters.

Phones lifted toward waiting faces.

Overlapping announcements dissolve into human sound.

The brothers emerge carrying winter in their clothes.

Heat finds them even indoors.

Ade removes his coat first.

ADE
I have made a tactical error.

Bode removes his jacket.

Folds it over one arm.

His body changes before his voice does.

Shoulders loose.

Pace certain.

BODE
Passports in your front pockets.

Keep the claim tags.

Do not give a bag to anyone I have not
spoken to.

Malik opens his document case.

BODE (CONT'D)
Close it.

MALIK
The connection—

BODE
Close it, Malik.

Malik looks around.

Nothing is arranged for his comfort.

He closes the case.

They enter the current.

INT. MURTALA MUHAMMED AIRPORT - BAGGAGE HALL - LATER

A carousel turns beneath fluorescent light.

One suitcase.

Then none.

Then twelve at once.

People surge.

Malik reads every tag.

Ade watches three different exits.

Kai watches the bags.

Not labels.

Damage.

Tape.

Wheel patterns.

A PORTER, twenties, approaches Bode with an empty trolley.

PORTER
Oga, make I help you.

BODE
This one.

He points to Malik's suitcase.

BODE (CONT'D)
Leave the black case with him.

The porter nods.

PORTER
No wahala.

He retrieves the suitcase cleanly.

Malik watches it leave his hand.

Bode watches Malik allow it.

Another black suitcase appears.

Same brand as Ade's.

Same size.

Ade reaches.

KAI
Not yours.

ADE
It is literally mine.

KAI
Your left wheel is grey.

That one is black.

Ade checks.

Black.

A WOMAN beside them checks the tag.

WOMAN
This is mine.

ADE
Apparently I travel better in theory.

His actual suitcase appears two bags later.

Left wheel grey.

Kai pulls it free.

Pattern recognition with a practical use.

Malik notices.

Does not call it curiosity.

The porter loads the final bag.

BODE
Domestic terminal.

PORTER
I know road.

BODE
Good.

How much?

The porter names a price.

Bode looks at him.

PORTER
Oga, four big bags.

BODE
And one small trolley.

The porter smiles.

They negotiate in quick Nigerian Pidgin.

Not conflict.

Rhythm.

A fair price emerges.

Bode pays.

Ade pulls out American dollars.

Bode pushes his hand down.

BODE
Keep that before you make the price
international.

Ade puts it away.

ADE
I understood all of that.

BODE
Then why were you reaching for dollars?

Ade has no answer.

INT. MURTALA MUHAMMED AIRPORT - DOMESTIC TERMINAL - LATER

A terminal shuttle, one curbside negotiation and another line later—

The porter leads.

Bode beside him.

The brothers follow with the padded carry case between them.

Malik checks a clock.

Then his watch.

They disagree by four minutes.

He leaves both unchanged.

At the domestic counter, an AIRLINE ATTENDANT weighs the checked bags again.

Different allowance.

Different rules.

Ade's suitcase is overweight.

Again.

He looks at Malik.

Malik looks at Bode.

Bode opens his own suitcase.

ADE
What happens when we get home and you
have all my shoes?

BODE
I begin a better life.

The attendant laughs.

The tension breaks without making her the joke.

Malik transfers one of his document folders into Kai's backpack.

Not all four.

One.

He survives.

The padded carry case stays with them.

The attendant attaches a cabin tag.

DESTINATION:

CBQ.

CALABAR.

The letters are small.

The consequence is not.

INT. DOMESTIC AIRCRAFT - DAY

A smaller cabin.

Brighter.

No private screens.

No map to distrust.

The brothers sit on both sides of the aisle.

The travel urn beneath Malik's seat.

The empty brass urn above him, wrapped inside his carry-on.

Bode takes the window.

As the plane climbs, Lagos compresses.

Water becomes light.

Roads become lines.

Ade looks across the aisle.

ADE
You seem taller here.

BODE
You seem louder everywhere.

ADE
It's the altitude.

Bode looks out.

The land below grows green.

Not postcard green.

Dense.

Wet.

Layered.

The kind of green that conceals its own depth.

Kai raises his camera.

Then remembers the vanished destination.

He lowers it.

Uses his eyes.

Bode notices.

Says nothing.

EXT. MARGARET EKPO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT - RUNWAY - AFTERNOON

The aircraft lands hard enough to wake everyone.

Heat shimmers above the runway.

Beyond the tarmac—

Calabar waits beneath a white sky.

INT. MARGARET EKPO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT - ARRIVALS - LATER

Smaller than Lagos.

Closer.

The room holds every voice.

Ceiling fans push warm air in slow circles.

The brothers wait beside the baggage belt.

No winter coats now.

Sweat gathers immediately.

The padded carry case remains in Malik's hand.

The checked bags arrive.

One.

Two.

Three.

Not four.

The belt keeps moving.

Then stops.

Malik looks toward the service desk.

MALIK
Ade.

ADE
Before you say anything—

MALIK
Your suitcase is not here.

ADE
That was roughly what I expected you
to say.

An UNIFORMED PORTER has already loaded three bags onto a trolley.

He reaches for Kai's camera bag.

Malik pulls it back.

PORTER
Oga, I go carry am reach outside.

MALIK
No, thank you.

The porter continues securing the luggage.

PORTER
No worry.

Bode steps between them.

Not aggressive.

At home in the negotiation.

BODE
My brother, abeg.

We never talk price.

PORTER
Na small thing.

BODE
Small thing no dey start after you don
carry person load.

The porter grins.

Caught.

Not ashamed.

PORTER
Oga, na airport.

BODE
And na trolley.

They regard one another.

The porter names his price.

Bode cuts it in half.

The porter adds one quarter.

Bode agrees.

A contract made without paper.

PORTER
Your other bag dey there.

He points across the hall.

Ade's suitcase sits beside a family with matching black luggage.

A TEENAGE BOY studies its tag.

Kai sees the grey wheel.

KAI
That's his.

They cross.

The boy's MOTHER reads the name.

MOTHER
Oku?

ADE
Unfortunately.

She gives him the bag.

MOTHER
You people should mark your luggage.

ADE
My brother marks everything.

MALIK
Not luggage.

MOTHER
Then he should start.

She walks away.

Malik looks at the suitcase.

Pulls a red luggage strap from his document case.

Ade watches him fasten it around the bag.

ADE
You had that the whole time?

MALIK
Contingency.

ADE
For the problem you did not prevent?

Malik tightens the strap.

Not too tight.

MALIK
Practice.

Bode hears his own word returned.

Almost smiles.

The porter pushes the trolley toward the exit.

This time, with permission.

INT./EXT. MARGARET EKPO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT - EXIT - CONTINUOUS

The automatic doors open.

Heat enters like a body.

Kai's camera lens fogs white.

The entire city disappears.

He stops beneath the awning.

Wipes one small circle into the glass.

Through it—

Cars.

Palm shadows.

People calling greetings across traffic.

And on the opposite curb—

A hand-painted placard:

OKU — FOUR.

The sign fills the clear circle.

Everything around it remains clouded.

Kai lowers the camera.

Looks directly.

The sign is still there.

Bode follows his gaze.

For the first time since Vancouver—

He looks relieved.

BODE
Come.

The brothers step into the heat.

Together.

CUT TO BLACK.

# SEQUENCE VII — THE ROAD HOME

EXT. CALABAR AIRPORT - PICKUP LANE - CONTINUOUS

The hand-painted placard lowers.

Behind it stands EYO OKU, 51.

Lean.

Pressed short-sleeved shirt already darkening at the collar.

Car keys looped around one finger.

The patient posture of a man who has spent years keeping other people's things alive.

He looks at Bode.

Relief reaches his face first.

Then judgement.

EYO
Bode Oku.

You still remember road?

BODE
You came to the airport.

EYO
Because you forgot it.

They embrace.

Not ceremonially.

Hard.

Years compressed into a few seconds neither man will discuss.

When they separate, Eyo keeps one hand on Bode's shoulder.

Checks him.

Older.

Thinner.

Still here.

Then he turns to the brothers.

He does not ask who is who.

EYO
Malik.

Malik shifts the padded carry case into his other hand.

EYO
Ade.

Ade offers a tired salute.

EYO
And Kai.

Kai's camera hangs uselessly beneath its fogged lens.

ADE
Were there photographs?

EYO
Bode talks when he is worried.

BODE
I gave names.

EYO
You gave reports.

Eyo studies Malik's document case.

Ade's red-strapped suitcase.

Kai's camera.

Three reports confirmed.

His attention settles on the padded carry case.

The humour leaves him.

EYO
And this is Brother Solomon.

Malik looks at the case.

MALIK
His ashes.

EYO
I know what you carried.

Eyo reaches for one handle.

Malik does not release it.

A beat.

MALIK
I have him.

Eyo recognizes the grip.

Does not challenge it.

EYO
Then hold am well.

The road has not improved for anybody.

He takes Ade's suitcase instead.

EYO
Una welcome.

Come.

Make we move before this sun roast person.

ADE
It has started with me.

EYO
That one na airport.

Calabar never start.

EXT. AIRPORT PARKING AREA - MOMENTS LATER

An older TOYOTA LAND CRUISER waits beneath a flame tree.

Clean.

Repaired.

One rear door a slightly different shade of silver.

Eyo opens the back.

The porter loads the luggage.

Malik supervises without correcting him.

Almost.

The empty brass urn remains wrapped inside Malik's carry-on.

The birch travel urn stays in his hands.

Eyo closes the rear hatch.

It rebounds.

He lifts it again.

Slams harder.

The latch catches.

EYO
Everything here needs persuasion.

ADE
Malik is going to love it.

INT. LAND CRUISER - MOVING - AFTERNOON

Eyo drives.

Bode beside him.

Malik and Ade in the second row.

Kai behind them among the luggage.

The travel urn rests across Malik's thighs.

Both hands around it.

The air conditioner exhales without conviction.

Eyo strikes the dashboard once.

The fan blows harder.

EYO
You see?

ADE
Violence.

Finally, a system I understand.

Malik loosens the top button of his shirt.

MALIK
How long to the house?

EYO
Depends on road.

MALIK
Approximately.

EYO
Depends how road feels about
approximation.

Bode looks out the window.

Familiar streets arriving faster than memory can receive them.

EYO
Una don chop?

ADE
Three time zones ago.

EYO
That one no be food.

ADE
It had plastic around it.

EYO
Exactly.

EXT. CALABAR STREETS - MOVING - AFTERNOON

The city meets them without introduction.

Low buildings stained by rain.

Deep gutters.

Church signs.

School walls painted with alphabets.

Keke threading between cars.

Market umbrellas holding islands of colour against the white sky.

Children in uniform walk in pairs.

A woman balances a tray of oranges on her head while answering her phone.

Nobody pauses to become scenery.

Kai wipes his lens.

Raises the camera.

Through the glass—

Faces.

Shop fronts.

Power lines crossing and recrossing.

A BARBER looks directly into the lens from his doorway.

Kai lowers the camera.

The barber nods once.

Kai nods back.

Permission negotiated too late.

At a traffic light, a GIRL approaches with cold bottles of water in a basin.

Ade lowers his window.

Eyo names the price before the girl does.

She rolls her eyes.

GIRL
Uncle, allow me do business.

EYO
Do business.

No do robbery.

She hands four bottles through the window.

Ade pays.

Too much.

The girl counts it.

ADE
Keep it.

GIRL
God bless you.

She is gone before Eyo can object.

The light changes.

EYO
Tomorrow, the whole road will know
Canadian people have arrived.

ADE
We prefer philanthropic.

MALIK
You gave her four times the price.

ADE
She had water.

I had Canadian money and no local
judgement.

The exchange was honest.

Kai passes one bottle forward to Bode.

Bode has lowered his window.

Hot air moves across his face.

He breathes it in.

Eyo notices.

EYO
Now you know say you reach.

BODE
I knew at the airport.

EYO
Airport na waiting room.

This one—

He gestures through the windshield.

EYO
—this one is the place.

Bode drinks.

Does not answer.

The city continues around him.

EYO
Everybody dey house.

BODE
Who is everybody?

EYO
Everybody you did not tell not to come.

Ade leans forward.

ADE
How many people is everybody?

EYO
If you count them, somebody will be
insulted.

ADE
Finally.

Family math.

Malik opens the itinerary on his phone.

No address for the house.

Only coordinates.

He enters them.

A blue route appears.

Forty-eight minutes.

He watches the number become fifty-one.

Eyo glances at him in the mirror.

EYO
That thing know road?

MALIK
Satellite does.

EYO
Satellite no enter pothole.

The light changes again.

They move.

INT. LAND CRUISER - MOVING - LATER

Traffic loosens.

Concrete gives way to wider intervals of green.

The brothers' exhaustion settles differently.

Ade's head rests against the window.

Eyes closed.

Not asleep.

Malik studies the route.

Kai watches Bode and Eyo in the rear-view mirror.

Eyo lowers his voice.

EYO
You tell dem the name?

BODE
No.

EYO
You still believe silence na lock.

BODE
I believe stories create routes.

Malik looks up.

MALIK
Routes for what?

Neither man pretends not to hear him.

Bode turns halfway in his seat.

BODE
Attention.

Invitation.

Sometimes both.

MALIK
Whose name?

BODE
The woman in the photograph.

MALIK
You know it.

BODE
Yes.

MALIK
Then tell us.

BODE
Inside the house.

With the doors closed.

EYO
Walls never stopped it before.

BODE
They gave us time.

The Land Cruiser rolls over a broken patch of road.

The urn shifts.

Malik catches it immediately.

Eyo watches him in the mirror.

EYO
The house has been closed a long time.

We opened it for you.

MALIK
That is also not an answer.

EYO
It is the answer I can give while
driving.

Malik waits.

Eyo keeps his eyes on the road.

Bode does not rescue either of them.

Ade opens one eye.

ADE
For anyone keeping score, the Canadians
are losing.

Malik looks back at his phone.

The blue route orders them left.

Eyo drives straight.

MALIK
You missed the turn.

EYO
No.

MALIK
The route says left.

EYO
That road washed out last rainy season.

MALIK
The map was updated last month.

EYO
Then the map should come and drive.

Ade closes his eye again.

ADE
It has my vote.

Bode points ahead.

BODE
This way is faster.

Malik looks from the two men to the blue route.

He turns off the screen.

Does not put the phone away.

EXT. OUTSKIRTS ROAD - MOVING - LATE AFTERNOON

The road narrows.

Red earth shows through broken asphalt.

Compounds sit farther apart.

Cassava.

Plantain.

Raffia palms leaning toward unseen water.

Laundry moves on lines behind low walls.

Smoke from cooking fires lies thin beneath the trees.

The Land Cruiser passes a concrete bridge over a brown, slow-moving channel.

Eyo taps the steering wheel toward it.

EYO
Your father jumped from there when he
was fifteen.

All three brothers look.

ADE
On purpose?

BODE
That depends who tells it.

EYO
He told everybody he could swim.

BODE
He could not.

EYO
Still cannot.

The laugh escapes Ade before he can decide whether death permits it.

Kai laughs too.

Malik tries not to.

Fails.

For several seconds—

Solomon is not a secret.

Not an urn.

A frightened fifteen-year-old swallowing river water while his family laughed from a bridge.

The moment passes.

But it leaves the brothers breathing easier.

Kai raises his camera.

Frames the bridge behind them.

This time, he records what is there.

EXT. FOREST ROAD - MOVING - LATER

The sky lowers.

Green crowds both sides of the road.

The air beyond the windows looks almost liquid.

Eyo slows for a deep rut.

The Land Cruiser tilts.

Malik braces the urn against his chest.

Kai looks past him.

Between two enormous trees—

Something too deliberate for the forest.

A LOW STONE STRUCTURE.

No higher than a child.

Half swallowed by the roots of a silk-cotton tree.

At its centre:

A narrow wooden panel.

Dark with age.

Bound once with a strip of faded RED FIBRE.

No sign.

No path visible from the road.

KAI
Slow down.

Eyo brakes gently.

Ade wakes.

MALIK
What happened?

Kai twists toward the rear window.

KAI
There was something in the tree.

Eyo's eyes move to Bode.

Only for a moment.

BODE
What did you see?

KAI
Stone.

Like a door.

Inside the roots.

Eyo drives on.

KAI
Can we stop?

BODE
No.

The answer is immediate.

Not mysterious.

Protective.

Kai looks at him.

KAI
What is it?

BODE
An old boundary.

KAI
For the house?

BODE
Not yours to cross.

KAI
That is not what I asked.

Bode holds his gaze.

BODE
It is what you need to know.

Malik hears the echo of Eyo's answer.

Another closed door disguised as protection.

Kai checks the footage.

Windshield glare.

Leaves.

Motion.

Then—

Three blurred frames of stone held inside roots.

Real.

He pauses on the clearest one.

The wooden panel.

The faded red binding.

Bode looks back.

BODE
Keep the picture if you need it.

Just do not confuse a picture with
permission.

Kai lowers the camera.

KAI
Did Dad know about it?

Bode turns forward.

BODE
Your father knew what boundaries were
for.

Outside, the trees stream past.

Malik studies the back of Bode's head.

MALIK
Did he respect them?

Bode does not answer.

He does not need to.

EXT. OKU FAMILY ROAD - LATE AFTERNOON

The first rain strikes the windshield.

Large drops.

Widely spaced.

Eyo turns off the main road onto packed red earth.

Malik's phone loses the route.

The blue line ends in blank green.

He looks at it.

Then locks the screen.

Ahead—

A metal gate between rendered pillars.

Faded letters remain across the arch:

OKU.

Eyo sounds the horn.

Two short.

One long.

The gate opens before the final note dies.

EXT. OKU FAMILY COMPOUND - CONTINUOUS

The Land Cruiser enters.

The house from the photograph waits at the far end.

White walls weathered toward cream.

A rust-red roof.

Deep veranda.

Green wooden shutters.

Repairs visible beside older repairs.

Not abandoned.

Maintained.

Enduring.

Beside it—

The massive tree.

Larger now.

Its roots have lifted the paving stones and reached toward the veranda.

The compound is already alive.

Children abandon a football game.

Women emerge from the side kitchen carrying covered bowls.

Men rise from plastic chairs beneath the veranda.

Someone calls Bode's name.

Then everyone does.

EYO
You asked who is everybody.

Ade looks at the waiting family.

ADE
I should have worn better shoes.

MALIK
You are wearing shoes.

ADE
Exactly.

The Land Cruiser stops.

For a moment, no one inside moves.

Bode looks at the house.

The tree.

The faces waiting for him.

Eyo switches off the engine.

The air conditioner dies.

Family sound enters all at once.

EYO
You fit come down.

BODE
I know.

EYO
Your body never hear.

Bode opens his door.

EXT. OKU FAMILY COMPOUND - CONTINUOUS

The family folds around him.

Hands.

Shoulders.

Names spoken with affection and accusation in equal measure.

Bode disappears into homecoming.

The brothers climb out more slowly.

They are immediately visible as outsiders.

Not because anyone rejects them.

Because everyone recognizes them.

Eyes linger.

Comparisons pass silently from face to face.

Then the family parts for AUNTIE ENO, late sixties.

Strong.

Elegant.

The intact young woman from the 1989 photograph, transformed by thirty-seven years without becoming less recognizable.

Solomon and Bode's cousin.

A house key tied into the corner of her wrapper.

She stops before Bode.

ENO
You took your time.

BODE
I know.

Eno touches his face.

Not forgiveness.

Proof.

Then she looks at Malik.

Then Ade.

Then Kai.

ENO
Solomon divided his face among three
children.

Ade glances at his brothers.

ADE
He could have divided the height more
fairly.

Eno considers him.

Then laughs.

The family follows.

Ade's shoulders lower.

His work has begun.

Eno's eyes settle on the padded carry case.

Malik holds it tighter.

She places one palm against the case.

No prayer.

No performance.

Only contact.

ENO
You bring am.

MALIK
We brought him.

The correction matters.

She looks at all three brothers.

Nods.

ENO
Then enter.

Family members reach for luggage.

Malik starts to object.

Stops himself.

He lets a YOUNG MAN take his suitcase.

Not the urn.

One thing at a time.

Kai hangs back.

He removes the creased 1989 photograph from his camera bag.

Holds it against the living house.

Same veranda.

Same shutters.

Same massive tree.

In the photograph, four young people stand before roots that end several feet from the steps.

Solomon.

Bode.

Eno.

The woman whose face was destroyed.

Kai lowers the photograph.

Now—

One root has reached the threshold.

Family streams around it without looking down.

Malik enters first with the travel urn.

Ade follows.

Inside Bode's jacket—

The sealed MiniDV envelope.

Still unopened.

Kai remains outside.

The camera in one hand.

The damaged photograph in the other.

He raises the photograph once more.

Aligns past and present.

The scratched-away face covers the open doorway.

A human-shaped absence filled with the darkness inside the house.

KAI
Who were you?

No answer.

Only family calling his name from within.

Kai lowers the photograph.

Steps over the root.

Enters.

CUT TO BLACK.
